Epidemic models

Compartment models

  • Susceptible-Infected-Recovered (SIR) model and its variants
  • Each individual is at exactly one stage at any time
  • Potentially goes from one stage to another

Classical assumptions governing the dynamics

  • Markovian
  • Homogeneous mixing

See e.g. Andersson and Britton (2000) (link)

First thing to do - look for existing models to see if we can adapt

  • Compartment models is one class of epidemic models which is very popular in the statistical literature
  • The classical compartment model is the SIR model. In this model, at any time point, each individual is in exactly one of the three stages, and there are some dynamic equations which affect the individuals potentially going from one stage to another.
  • There are some variants of the SIR model, for example you can remove the recovered stage, or add an exposed stage before infected stage, all depending on the data and the application.
  • One of the classical assumptions governing the dynamics is that the process of stage transitioning is Markovian.
  • The other assumption of homogeneous mixing means that each individual interacts with all the other individuals uniformly, so, for example, all persons susceptible at this time point, have the same probability of being infected by another infected individual.

Epidemic models

Network modelling

Identifiability issue

  • Inverse relationship between infection rate and edge inclusion probability
  • "Different explanations of the same outcome"
    (Britton and O’Neill, 2002)

A bigger problem - identifiability, because BRG retains the uniformity of the homogeneous mixing assumption

  • Give example, epidemic rate 1 and homogeneous mixing
  • Epidemic rate doubled, BRG with \(p=0.5\)
  • Theoretically same growth curve
  • Inference can't tell apart
  • Will come back in slides later
  • Let's take one step back and look at the models that characterise certain aspects of real-life networks

Network models

Power-law degree distribution

  • One main feature of real-life networks
  • A few nodes highly connected while a lot of nodes have very small degrees
  • Look at degree distribution on the log-scale

Network models

Barabási and Albert (1999): Preferential attachment (PA) model

  • Each new node enters the network one by one, with \(\mu\) new edges
  • Each existing node gets an edge with probability proportional to current degree


image source

One model that can capture this feature

  • two new edges each
  • earlier nodes are more likely to end up being the hubs

Network models

Small path lengths

  • Six degrees of separation

High clustering

  • Three typical nodes \(A,B\) and \(C\)
  • Assume \(A\leftrightarrow B\) and \(B\leftrightarrow C\)
  • Clustering coefficient: how likely that \(A\leftrightarrow C\)
  • BRG: whether each pair is connected is independent of other pairs a priori
  • Another feature which you may have heard - easy to get to other nodes in the network
  • One more feature - BRG quite the opposite

Network models

Watts and Strogatz (1998): Small world model

  • Start with a "well-structured" network
    • lattice
  • Add random links or rewire the edges


image source
  • To deal with these features, there is this small world model
  • a parameter governing the randomness of the network, which in turn affects clustering and path length

Network models

Epidemic modelling

Compartment models represented by ordinary differential equations (ODEs)

  • \(\displaystyle\frac{dS}{dt}=-\beta IS \qquad\qquad\frac{dI}{dt}=\beta IS-\gamma I \qquad\qquad\frac{dR}{dt}=\gamma I\)

Incorporate network aspects as covariate

  • E.g. same parameter values for individuals with same degree
  • Comprehensive review by Pastor-Satorras, Castellano, Van Mieghem and Vespignani (2015)

Quite remote from previously introduced statistical models

Some people have tried to incorporate epidemic an epidemic into a network model, at least for the PA model

  • points in slide
  • But they focus on the model structure and possible simulating from them, and don't really care about the inference
  • quite difficult because of the number of parameters

Ingredients

Population: \(m\) nodes/individuals

The epidemic times \(\boldsymbol{I}=(I_1,I_2,\ldots,I_m)\)

  • Susceptible-Infected (SI) model
  • Markovian, constant infection rate \(\beta\)

The underlying graph/network \(\boldsymbol{G}=\{G_{ij}\}_{m\times m}\)

  • Preferential attachment model, parameter \(\mu\)
  • \(G_{ij}=1\) if \(i\leftrightarrow j\) for \(i\neq j\), \(0\) otherwise

The transmission tree \(\boldsymbol{P}=\{P_{ij}\}_{m\times m}\)

  • \(P_{ij}=1\) if node \(j\) is infected by \(i\), \(0\) otherwise
  • After shopping around for a while, we were still not able to find the perfect model, so we have to construct our own
  • But first we have to get the ingredients.
  • Nodes and individuals interchangeable, so are graph and network
  • Using the adjacency matrix representation, G and P are matrices with ones and zeros

Recipe

Step 1: Obtain new edges for the ordered nodes

Index the nodes by their order of entering the network

One edge to start with: nodes \(1\leftrightarrow2\)

Node \(i~(>2)\) brings in \(x_i\) new edges

  • \(x_i=\mu\) (constant) in original PA model too restrictive
  • \(x_i\sim\) truncated Poission \((\mu)\) (mean \(=\frac{\mu}{1-\exp(-\mu)}\))

Relationship between \(x_i\) and \(G_{ij}\)

\(x_i=\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}G_{ij}~\text{for}~i>2\)

  • let's go through how we build the model, which is quite intuitive because of the nature of the preferential attachment model and the epidemic model. Therefore the next few slides can be seen as a recipe for simulating from the model, as well as a recipe of calculating the likelihood. We will look at both along the way.
  • In order to construct or simulate from the preferential attachment model, we first label the nodes by \(1,2,\ldots,m\) according to their order of entering the network, and then obtain the sequence of new edges.
  • But first we need something in the network to start with, so we assume initially there are two nodes that are connected to each other.
  • For each subsequent node, there is a number of new edges it brings in. This number is a constant in the original PA model, but this makes the model too restrictive.
  • Truncated Poisson to ensure each node has at least one edge, and therefore the graph is connected.
  • This number of new edges has a direct relationship with the G's, as it is the sum of edges the node has with those who are already in the network. This can be seen easily in the toy example.

Recipe

Step 1: Obtain new edges for the ordered nodes

\(\sum_{i=3}^{m}x_{i}+1=\sum\sum_{j<i}G_{ij}=\frac{1}{2}\sum\sum_{i\neq j}G_{ij}\)

\(\sum\text{(new edges)} + 1 = \text{total no. of edges} |G| = \frac{1}{2}\sum\text{(individual degrees)}\)

Toy example: \(m=8,\mu=3\) 
##                     
## [1,] . 1 1 1 1 1 1 .
## [2,] 1 . 1 1 1 1 . 1
## [3,] 1 1 . . 1 . . .
## [4,] 1 1 . . . 1 . .
## [5,] 1 1 1 . . 1 1 .
## [6,] 1 1 . 1 1 . . .
## [7,] 1 . . . 1 . . .
## [8,] . 1 . . . . . .
  • Node 3 enters the network with two new edges, connects to nodes 1 and 2.
  • Node 4 enters the network also with two new edges, and connects to nodes 1 and 2.
  • Node 5 enters the network with three new edges, and connects to nodes 1, 2 and 3.
  • We will discuss the rule of picking these nodes later on, but the new edges can be seen as the partial row or column sums of the individual elements Gij.
  • Therefore we can establish the relationship that the sum of new edges plus 1 is equal to the total number of edges, which is essentially the sum of either the upper or the lower half of the matrix, because G is symmetric.

Recipe

Step 1: Obtain new edges for the ordered nodes

Likelihood: \[ L_1(\boldsymbol{G};\mu)=\prod_{i=3}^{m}\frac{e^{-\mu}\mu^{x_i}}{x_i!(1-e^{-\mu})}\\ \quad\quad\quad~~~=\frac{e^{-(m-2)\mu}\mu^{|G|-1}}{(1-e^{-\mu})^{m-2}\prod_{i=3}^{m}(x_i!)} \]

Total number of edges sufficient for \(\mu\)

  • As we assume independence between the number of new edges for different nodes, we can easily write down the likelihood
  • Turn the sum of x's to the total number of edges minus 1
  • Retain the product of factorials as it will get cancelled later on.
  • So we can see that the total number of edges is sufficient for \(\mu\)

Recipe

Step 2: Construct the underlying network

When node \(i\) enters

  • \(x_i\) existing nodes chosen from \(\{1,2,\ldots,i-1\}\)
  • Weighted sampling without replacement
  • Weight of existing node \(j = \frac{\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}{\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}\)

Exact likelihood

  • Go through all \(x_i!\) permutations of the selected nodes
  • When \(x=1,2,3,4,5,6,7,\ldots,~x!=1,2,6,24,120,720,5040,\ldots\)
  • Computationally not feasible

So we have generated the new edges, but we haven't covered how the network is formed, which means how we arrive at this G

  • Basically, when node \(i\) enters the network, it chooses \(x_i\) existing nodes from \(\{1,2,\ldots,i-1\}\), with weights proportional to these nodes current degrees.
  • As the process goes on, the nodes which have a higher degrees will be more likely to get an edge when the next node enters
  • This kind of positive feedback mechanism is the central rule of the preferential attachment model
  • So now when we are calculating the likelihood, we are essentially calculating the probability of picking the selected nodes under a weighted sampling scheme without replacement.
  • It is very straightforward to simulate under weighted sampling without replacement, but to compute the exact likelihood, we need to go through all the permutations of the selected nodes, and then average the probabilities.
  • This is not quite feasible because it is not unlikely to simulate an \(x_i\) to be, for example, 6 or 7.

Recipe

Step 2: Construct the underlying network

Approximation by likelihood under weighted sampling with replacement

Contribution by node \(i\)'s new edges: \[ L_{2i}=x_i!\times\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}} {\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}\right)^{G_{ij}} \]

Likelihood by the process of adding new edges: \[ L_2(\boldsymbol{G}):=\prod_{i=3}^{m}L_{2i}= \prod_{i=3}^{m}(x_i!)\times \prod_{i=3}^{m}\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}} {\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}\right)^{G_{ij}} \]

  • A quick fix is approximating the likelihood by that under weighted sampling with replacement.
  • A small simulation study: simulate from version without replacement, fit the version with replacement, still able to recover the parameters
  • Furthermore, it contains the product of factorial, which gets cancelled with the likelihood of new edges, and simplifies the overall expression
  • so \(L_1\) involves \(\mu\) and total number of edges only, while \(L_2\) involves the individual elements of \(G\) only

Recipe

Step 3: Spread the epidemic on the given network

Index the nodes by their epidemic (temporal) order

Infected node \(i\) makes infectious contacts

  • with its network neighbours
  • at points of Poisson process with rate \(\beta\sum_{j=1}^{m}G_{ij}\)

Likelihood independent of transmission tree \(\boldsymbol{P}\)

\(\pi(\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\beta)=\beta^{m-1}\exp\left(-\beta\sum\sum_{(i,j):G_{ij}=1}\left[(I_j-I_i)\vee0\right]\right)\\ \qquad\quad~=\beta^{m-1}\exp\left(-\beta\sum_{i=1}^{m-1}\sum_{j=i+1}^{m}G_{ij}(I_j-I_i)\right)\)

  • After generating the network, we can spread the epidemic. Whether the network is a preferential attachment one or a bernoulli random graph or anything else does not affect the rule of epidemic spreading. It only affects the end product, that is how fast the epidemic is spreading, or simply the growth curve. The process only depends on the dynamic equation.
  • In order to calculate the likelihood, we have to first index the nodes by their epidemic order. Then each infected individual affects its susceptible neighbours according to a Poisson process with rate a constant multiplied by the number of suscetible neighbours.
  • Then we can obtain the following expression, which we can see is independent of the transmission tree.

Recipe

Step 3: Spread the epidemic on the given network

So where is \(\boldsymbol{P}\) gone?

  • "Uniform distribution on the set of all possible infection pathways" (Britton and O’Neill, 2002)

\[ \pi(\boldsymbol{P}|\boldsymbol{G})\propto \prod_{j=2}^m \frac{1}{~\sum_{i=1}^{j-1}G_{ij}~} \times \prod_{i=1}^{m-1}\prod_{j=i+1}^{m}\mathbf{1}\left\{P_{ij}\leq G_{ij}\right\} \]

Posterior of \(\boldsymbol{G}\) involves \(\boldsymbol{P}\)

  • If \(P_{ij}=1\), \(G_{ij}=1\) with probability 1 (same for \(G_{ji}\)) a posteriori
  • More details in inference

So you may ask, where is the information provided by the transmission tree?

  • It actually follows a uniform distribution on all possible infection pathways given by the network.
  • For example, if an infected individual has four susceptible neighbours, each of its neighbours will have a probability of a quarter to be infected by this particular individual.
  • So you can trace transmission tree along the graph and calculate the uniform probability infection by infection, then multiply all the probabilities together to get this likelihood.

Recipe

Step 4: Connect the network and the epidemic

Epidemic order not necessarily the same as network order

  • Fix the labelling of nodes by epidemic order
  • Introduce variable \(\boldsymbol{\sigma}\) - permutation of \(\{1,2,\ldots,m\}\)

Convert from epidemic order to network order

  • Replace \(\boldsymbol{G}\) by \(\boldsymbol{G}^{'}=f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma})\) when computing \(L_1(\cdot;\mu)\) and \(L_2(\cdot)\)
  • The recipe so far is quite straightforward, but the problem is that we need a separate set of labels to calculate the likelihood in each step.
  • So our method is to fix the labelling according the epidemic order, and introduce a vector variable which gives us the ordering of how these nodes enter the network.
  • And then to calculate the likelihood, we stick to the graph G given by the epidemic order, but create a G prime by converting G using sigma, and substitute this G prime into L1 and L2. This function f simply takes it a matrix and outputs a matrix of the same dimensions. Let's go back to the toy example to make it easier to understand.

Recipe

Step 4: Connect the network and the epidemic

Toy example continued: \(m=8,\mu=3\)

  • \(\boldsymbol{\sigma}=(5,3,8,2,6,4,7,1)\)
## [1] "G"
##                     
## [1,] . 1 1 1 1 1 1 .
## [2,] 1 . 1 1 1 1 . 1
## [3,] 1 1 . . 1 . . .
## [4,] 1 1 . . . 1 . .
## [5,] 1 1 1 . . 1 1 .
## [6,] 1 1 . 1 1 . . .
## [7,] 1 . . . 1 . . .
## [8,] . 1 . . . . . .
## [1] "G_prime = f(G, sigma)"
##                     
## [1,] . 1 . 1 1 . 1 1
## [2,] 1 . . 1 . . . 1
## [3,] . . . 1 . . . .
## [4,] 1 1 1 . 1 1 . 1
## [5,] 1 . . 1 . 1 . 1
## [6,] . . . 1 1 . . 1
## [7,] 1 . . . . . . 1
## [8,] 1 1 . 1 1 1 1 .
  • The adjacency matrix on the left is the graph according to the epidemic, so row 1 or column 1 corresponds to the epidemic node 1.
  • The ordering sigma here means epidemic nodes 5 and 3 are the only edge when the network was created, followed by epidemic node 8, and so on. So G prime is simply rearranging the rows and columns simultaneously of G.
  • We can also see this ordering is actually not possible in reality, or equivalently it will result in a likelihood of 0, because of the void here.
  • This is because, as we can see from G, epidemic node 8 is only connected to epidemic node 2. But in G prime, epidemic node 8 comes in BEFORE epidemic node 2, and so there's no neighbours it can connect to when it enters the network.
  • So whenever you observe this pattern of zeros you can be sure that the ordering will give a likelihood of zero.

Bayesian inference

\(\boldsymbol{G}\) is usually unknown

\(~~~~\pi(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu|\boldsymbol{P},\boldsymbol{I})\\ \propto\pi(\boldsymbol{P},\boldsymbol{I},\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\\ =\pi(\boldsymbol{P},\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\\ =\pi(\boldsymbol{P}|\boldsymbol{G})\times\pi(\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\beta)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{G}|\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\qquad(\boldsymbol{P}~\bot~\boldsymbol{I}~\text{given}~\boldsymbol{G})\\ =\pi(\boldsymbol{P}|\boldsymbol{G})\times\pi(\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\beta)\times L_1\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu\right)L_2(\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma})\right)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma})\pi(\beta)\pi(\mu)\)

Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm straightforward

  • Similar latent approach if \(\boldsymbol{P}\) is also unknown
  • Now we have got all the components and we know how to construct them, we can go on and carry out the infernce.
  • But it is very common that G is unknown, and so it is quite natural to consider a Bayesian approach to do inference, by considering the edges of G as latent variables, and estimate their posterior edge inclusion probabilities with the other parameters.
  • We break down the posterior to these few components, and you can see that each component refers to a step we have seen just now, of course given the values of G.
  • Also, once we specify the priors, which we assume to be independent, we can write out the whole line explicity, and this gives rise to a straightforward MCMC algorithm.
  • This MCMC scheme can be used even when P is also unknown, as we can use a similar approach to G to calculate the posterior probability of each element of P. But we just stick to P being known here.

Bayesian inference

Uninformative priors

\(\beta\sim\text{Gamma}(a_\beta, \text{rate}=b_\beta)\)

\(\mu\sim\text{Gamma}(a_\mu, \text{rate}=b_\mu)\)

\(\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma})=(m!)^{-1}\)

  • These are the priors we use, and we set the hyperparameters such that the priors for beta and mu are uninformative.
  • For sigma, we just assume any permutation has the same prior probability.

Bayesian inference

Posteriors

\(\beta|\ldots\sim \text{Gamma}\left(a_\beta+m-1,\text{rate}=b_\beta+\sum_{i=1}^{m-1}\sum_{j=i+1}^{m}G_{ij}(I_j-I_i)\right)\)

\(\pi(\mu|\ldots)\propto e^{-(b_{\mu}+m-2)\mu}\mu^{a_{\mu}+|G|-2}(1-e^{-\mu})^{2-m}\boldsymbol{1}\{\mu>0\}\)

\(\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma}|\ldots)\propto L_1\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu\right)L_2(\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma})\right)\)

Exploring permutation space

  • Bezáková, Kalai and Santhanam (2006): link
  • Random insertion
  • More efficient than random swap

These are the posteriors.

  • \(Beta\) got a Gibbs step, and \(mu\) got a Metropolis step.
  • We can't use a Gibbs step for \(mu\) because we used the zero truncated Poisson distribution, not the original Poisson distribution.
  • As for sigma, we also use a Metropolis step, as long as we can propose another permutation to update, and put the proposed value into the product of L1 and L2, then apply the standard acceptance-rejection procedure of a Metropolis step.
  • So the question is how to explore the permutation space, and we use the random insertion method suggested by this paper.
  • To give you an idea, imagine you have a deck of cards, which represent sigma. Now you randomly and uniformly take one card out, and put it back in another position, also randomly and uniformly.
  • The authors claim that this method is empirically more efficient than the classical method of randomly swapping two adjacent cards, so we just go with this method, as long as the ordering is mixing properly.
  • Also, it takes very little time to propose and update sigma, compared to updating the elements of G, so we are not really concerned about optimising the number of insertions in each iteration.

Bayesian inference

Posteriors

\(\Pr(G_{ij}=1|P_{ij}=1,\ldots)=1\)

\(\boldsymbol{G}_0~(\boldsymbol{G}_1)\) the same as \(\boldsymbol{G}\) with \(G_{ij}\) and \(G_{ji}\) set to \(0 (1)\)

\(\Pr(G_{ij}=0|P_{ij}=0,\boldsymbol{G}_{-ij},\ldots)\propto \displaystyle\frac{L_1(f(\boldsymbol{G}_0,\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu)~L_2(f(\boldsymbol{G}_0,\boldsymbol{\sigma}))} {\sum_{k=1,k\neq i}^{j-1}G_{kj}}\)

\(\Pr(G_{ij}=1|P_{ij}=0,\boldsymbol{G}_{-ij},\ldots)\propto \displaystyle\frac{L_1(f(\boldsymbol{G}_1,\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu)~L_2(f(\boldsymbol{G}_1,\boldsymbol{\sigma}))~e^{-\beta(I_j-I_i)}} {\sum_{k=1,k\neq i}^{j-1}G_{kj}+1}\)

Perfect?

  • Not quite

For each potential edge Gij, we divide into two cases.

  • The trivial case is that if Pij is equal to 1, which means i infects j, then i and j must be connected aposteriori.
  • The non-trivial case is when Pij is 0. In this case we can apply a Gibbs step to Gij.
  • First we define two G's, both the same as G except Gij is set to 0 in this G0 and 1 in this G1.
  • Then we calculate the weights under each scenario, we just use probability integral transform to determine the new current value of Gij.

So everything is perfect, right? Unfortunately, it's not the case when it comes to simulation study.

Simulation study

Scenarios

Simulate network only, estimate \((\mu,\boldsymbol{\sigma})\)

  • Good

Simulate network & epidemic, estimate \((\mu,\beta,\boldsymbol{\sigma})\) given \(\boldsymbol{G}\) (and \(\boldsymbol{I}\))

  • Good

Simulate network & epidemic, estimate \((\mu,\beta,\boldsymbol{\sigma},\boldsymbol{G})\) given \(\boldsymbol{P}\) and \(\boldsymbol{I}\)

  • Problematic
  • We created a few scenarios with different true values of the parameters, carried out the simulation, and fit the model to see if the inference recovers the true parameter values.
  • It works absolutely fine when only the network is simulated and backfit.
  • It even worked well when we also simulated the epidemic and fit the model by setting G to be known in the inference.
  • But because in reality G is usually unknown, we simply used the same set of simulated data but fit the model by not knowing G, which means we have to carry out this Gibbs step to infer all the individual elemtns of G.
  • The data we have for the inference is only P and I, and this is the case where the results become problematic.

Simulation study

Identifiability

Posterior of \(\mu\) depends not on its true value but on \(m\)

So what went wrong?

  • First of all, if you simulate from the model and then backfit to the simulated data, you would want the estimates of the parameters to be unbiased, consistent, etc., or at least in some sense close to its true value.
  • But that's not the case for \(\mu\) here.
  • It doesn't increase with the true value of \(\mu\), but strangely it increases with the population size.

Simulation study

Identifiability

\(\beta\) better, but not good enough

We also looked at \(\beta\), and sadly it's not doing good enough either, though it does not stay constant with its true value.

Simulation study

Identifiability

What about \(\ldots \alpha=\beta\times\mu\)?

But something miraculous happens when we multiply the the two parameters

  • we define the product to be alpha, and this is how the posterior mean of alpha looks like against its true value
  • At least one of the parameters can be identified, if we reparameterise the model to be \((\alpha, \mu)\)

Simulation study

Identifiability

Adding uncertainty for \(\alpha\)

We also look at uncertainty by adding 95\(\%\) credible intervals

  • a lot of uncertainty
  • but at least on the right track
  • identifying one parameter as good as we can get

Simulation study

Observations

Inverse relationship between epidemic rate \(\beta\) and parameter characterising network connectedness

  • Average number new edges \(\mu\) in PA model
  • Edge inclusion probability \(p\) in BRG model
    • Echoing observation by Britton and O’Neill (2002)

Under reparameterisation \(\alpha=\beta\mu\)

  • Identifying one parameter \((\alpha)\) as good as we can get
  • Mixing/convergence similar
  • Interpretation

That the parameters' product is identifiable actually tells us there is a inverse relationship between the

  • In PA it is beta and mu, in BRG it is beta and p
  • So this echoes the observation by Britton and O'Neill that there are different explanations of the same outcome.
  • Unless we put informative priors, we can really tell whether a high beta and small mu, or a low beta and large mu, is the more probable scenario giving rise to the data in hand

Still waiting for results!

Typical times taken per iteration:

  • \(m=100: 0.88\text{s}\)
  • \(m=200: 14\text{s}\)

Computational time \(O(m^4)\)

  • # potential edges \((G_{ij})\) to update \(O(m^2)\)
  • # computations involved in updating one edge \(O(m^2)\)

Data sets worth applying the model to

  • \(m = 350\) and up

But we can have some insights on the running times

  • exactly 16 times

Summary

Review on network epidemics

  • Statistical models assume BRG, unrealistic
  • Physical models focus on dynamics, difficult to do inference

Model and inference

  • PA model to grow network, SI model to spread epidemic
  • MCMC algorithm: Gibbs steps for \(\beta\) and individual edges \(G_{ij}\), Metropolis steps for \(\mu\) and \(\boldsymbol{\sigma}\)

Simulation study

  • Product of \(\beta\) and \(\mu\) identifiable but not individually
